# orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_resource (Resource)

Manages a [ServiceNow](https://www.servicenow.com/) credentials resource in
Orca Security. The same credentials back **both** ITSM and SIR templates —
under the hood Orca stores them under `service_name = "sn_incidents"`,
`type = "basic"` regardless of which kind of template (ITSM vs SIR) you
eventually attach.

Pair this resource with either
[`orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_itsm_template`](integration_servicenow_itsm_template.md)
or
[`orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_sir_template`](integration_servicenow_sir_template.md)
to actually start opening tickets.

## Example Usage

### Basic example

{{tffile "examples/resources/orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_resource/resource.tf"}}

### Sourcing the password from HashiCorp Vault

```terraform
data "vault_generic_secret" "sn" {
  path = "secret/servicenow/orca"
}

resource "orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_resource" "from_vault" {
  name           = "servicenow-prod"
  servicenow_url = "https://my-instance.service-now.com"
  username       = "orca-bot"
  password       = data.vault_generic_secret.sn.data["password"]
}
```

### Sourcing the password from a Kubernetes Secret

```terraform
data "kubernetes_secret" "sn" {
  metadata {
    name      = "servicenow-creds"
    namespace = "orca"
  }
}

resource "orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_resource" "from_k8s" {
  name           = "servicenow-prod"
  servicenow_url = "https://my-instance.service-now.com"
  username       = "orca-bot"
  password       = data.kubernetes_secret.sn.data["password"]
}
```

The same pattern works with AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secret Manager, Azure Key
Vault, and any other secret-store data source.

## Argument Reference

* `name` — (Required, String) Human-friendly name shown in the Orca UI.
* `servicenow_url` — (Required, String) ServiceNow instance URL, for example
  `https://my-instance.service-now.com`.
* `username` — (Required, String) ServiceNow account username for Basic auth.
* `password` — (Required, String, Sensitive) ServiceNow account password for
  Basic auth. Stored in Orca's secret store (SSM) and **never returned by the
  API**.

## Attribute Reference

* `id` — (String) Orca resource identifier (UUID). Use this value as
  `resource_id` on `orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_itsm_template` or
  `orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_sir_template`, or with
  `terraform import`.

## Password handling

The Orca API strips the password from `GET` responses (the value lives in SSM).
The provider keeps the value already in Terraform state to avoid a permanent
diff. Rotate through `terraform apply`; for out-of-band rotation use
`terraform apply -replace=orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_resource.example`.

## Secret-management best practices

* Never commit the password to `.tf` / `.tfvars`. Use a secret-manager data
  source, `TF_VAR_*`, or `-var-file` pointing at a gitignored file.
* `sensitive = true` redacts CLI output, but the password **does** land in the
  Terraform state file — use an encrypted remote backend (S3 + KMS, GCS,
  Terraform Cloud, etc.) and restrict read access.

## Import

```bash
terraform import orcasecurity_integration_servicenow_resource.example 11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555
```

After import, set the `password` argument in your configuration — the API
does not return it.
